messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

- Full HTTP request path: /users/signup
  - Rationale: The signup route is defined as router.post('/signup', signup) in routes/userRoutes.js, and the userRoutes are mounted under /users in index.js. No path parameters are present.

- Are all HTTP methods acceptable for this endpoint? false
  - Rationale: Only POST is defined for this endpoint. No other methods (GET, PUT, DELETE, etc.) are mapped to /users/signup.

- HEAD: false
  -Rationale: There is no explicit HEAD (or GET) handler for /users/signup. Express will not automatically treat this POST route as handling HEAD unless a GET/HEAD handler exists; since only POST is defined, HEAD is not supported by this code.

- POST: true
  - Rationale: The route is defined with POST for /users/signup.

- OPTIONS: true
  - Rationale: The app uses the CORS middleware (app.use(cors())). This middleware handles preflight OPTIONS requests for routes, so OPTIONS is effectively supported for this endpoint.

- TRACE: false
  - Rationale: There is no TRACE handler defined in the code.

- GET: false
  - Rationale: There is no GET handler for /users/signup.

- PUT: false
  - Rationale: There is no PUT handler for /users/signup.

- DELETE: false
  - Rationale: There is no DELETE handler for /users/signup.

- PATCH: false
  - Rationale: There is no PATCH handler for /users/signup.

Explanation:
- The final endpoint path is the combination of the base path /users (from app.use('/users', userRoutes)) and the route path /signup (from router.post('/signup', signup)).
- The only defined method for this endpoint is POST, so only POST is truly supported by the code.
- HEAD is not explicitly supported; Express would typically require a GET/HEAD route to automatically handle HEAD, which is not present here.
- OPTIONS is effectively supported due to the global CORS middleware, which handles preflight requests.
